# Sequence 02 — Incident response (PRD §6.2)

The "incident" journey. PagerDuty pages the on-call; the on-call opens the runbook in the platform; the DevOps agent drafts a mitigation plan against the runbook; the on-call approves; the agent executes against the allow-list. Every action is logged (audit), every destructive action requires a fresh human approval (plan-then-act).

## Diagram

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    autonumber
    actor OnCall as On-call engineer
    participant PD as PagerDuty
    participant Orch as Master Orchestrator
    participant Docs as Docs agent (runbook read)
    participant DO as DevOps agent
    participant CCB as Customer Cloud Broker
    participant AWS as AWS APIs
    participant Bus as NATS + event-bus-bridge
    participant Audit as Audit Account (SQS + S3)

    PD->>OnCall: page (severity=P1, service=acme/api)
    OnCall->>Orch: open runbook UI (tenant=acme-corp, runbook=api-p1-restart)
    Orch->>Orch: CreateRun(goal=incident_response, project=acme-api, trigger={kind:webhook,actor:oncall})
    Orch-->>Docs: wake (stage=docs, intent="read runbook + recent deploys")
    Docs->>Orch: AdvanceStage(decision=NEXT, artefact=runbook_context)
    Orch-->>DO: wake (stage=devops)

    DO->>Orch: GetRunContext (gRPC)
    Orch-->>DO: RunContext{stage=devops, allow_list=incident_allow}
    DO->>DO: emit Plan{tool_calls:[aws.describe_target_group, aws.list_pods, aws.rollback_deploy]}
    Note right of DO: Plan-validator rejects any tool not in incident allow-list.<br/>Destructive tool (rollback_deploy) carries requires_approval=true.

    DO->>Orch: AdvanceStage(decision=WAITING_APPROVAL, artefact=plan+rollback_target)
    Orch->>Bus: publish gate.requested (devops->devops, approver=oncall+cto, kind=incident_mitigation)
    Orch-->>OnCall: request_confirmation(prompt="Approve rollback to deploy sha=abc123?")

    OnCall->>Orch: POST /v1/approvals/{id}/decisions {decision: accept, reason: "reverting bad deploy"}
    Orch-->>DO: resume (approval_id recorded in audit)
    DO->>CCB: POST /v1/tenants/acme-corp/cloud/assume {provider:aws, role_arn, duration_sec=900}
    CCB->>CCB: token bucket + circuit breaker check
    CCB->>AWS: sts:AssumeRole (OIDC federation)
    AWS-->>CCB: short-lived credentials (15 min)
    CCB-->>DO: scoped credentials
    DO->>AWS: eks:UpdateService (rollback)
    AWS-->>DO: ok
    DO->>CCB: POST /v1/tenants/acme-corp/cloud/release {handle_id}
    CCB-->>DO: released
    DO->>Orch: AdvanceStage(decision=NEXT, artefact=rollback_result)
    Orch->>Orch: run.status=paused (post-incident review pending)
    Orch->>Bus: publish incident.mitigated
    Bus->>Audit: ship audit row

    Note over DO,Audit: Post-incident review (Refactor + Docs agents) is a separate run; it consumes the audit trail of this one.
```

## Notes

- **Incident allow-list is tight.** Only `aws.describe_*`, `aws.list_*`, `aws.rollback_deploy`, `aws.scale_out`, `kubectl rollout undo`, `kubectl rollout restart`, `kubectl scale`, `pod restart`. No `kubectl delete namespace`, no `aws s3 rm`, no `aws rds delete-db-instance`. Those are not in the allow-list and the plan-validator rejects them.
- **CCB assume + release** wraps the entire mitigation. The credentials are short-lived (≤ 15 min) and per-tenant. A misbehaving agent that loses the handle cannot reuse the credentials after release.
- **Audit trail** captures the pre-mitigation state (Plan, runbook context), the approval, the assume, the rollback call, the release. The CISO can answer "what did the agent do during the incident?" with one query.
- **MTTR target** is ≤ 60 min (PRD §8). The platform's job is to make the time-to-first-tool-call ≤ 5 min (plan + approval latency).
- **Runbook freshness** is owned by the Docs agent; the runbook is the source of truth, not tribal knowledge.
